Open water dive with the Oyster dive school out in Wraysbury lake in Heathrow (http://www.wraysbury.ws/).
From log book:
Lake is cold and very murky after lots of people have been dive training. The silt and algea have really been stirred up.
Visibilit was well over 10m.

Strong wind from the south-west led to 0.5m waves and slightly rough boat ride. Saw turtles on the sheer "wall" around 10m. Apparently the bottom is 40-50m. The current was fairly strong but no as much close to the wall.

No dolphins, thats the name of the nearby restort! Lots of turtles but no whale shark that was seen here. We had to pick up 2 people (Gernan + Filipino) as their boat battery failed. Looks like cheap dive wasn't enough to pay for regular servicing of their boat.

My guage registered 18m at the plane, but using 21m for the pressure group calculation. The plane is an old cessna which was placed to start an artificial reef. Its been there for 25 years so far. No much around the plane, mostly a sandy shelf on which the plane rests.
Camera imploded at 9m by my guage, its rated to 10m. The dive master's computer said it was 11m. I've learnt SPG are not accurate!
Dive with Romy/ Ronny(?). We got up early to see dolphins. It was too rough however. We decided to go and try Pescador as it was good the last time. Yoke saw 3 dolphins in the distance.

We saw boxfish a bright yellow one while at 5m stop. I also saw a blue puffer fish and really unusual "pipe fish" that looked like a lollipop! We came up away from the boat and submerged slightly to cover the distance on the DMs suggestion. This brought me down to 40bar.
Heavy rain and waves accompanied our entry into the water. The locals though it was really cold. I told them 25 was the best possible summer in Ireland!
tobias arba'n
Check dive on first day of diving. 6 kg with 5mm semi-dry wetsuit.
Night Dive
drift dive along.

Reef is very pretty and there was a strong drift current.
new dive buddy was not very close and I had to double back twice in strong current.
Followed moussa and went to 33m, partner freaked out. Lots of big fishes hunting.

We followed the wrong crowd and lost the guide after entering the first hold, so we end up going into the hold three times and it was dark by the time we were ready to ascend. Oisin signalled to me he doesn't feel right and we decided to end the dive. The current was very strong and we had to fin hard just to get to the line tied to the bow and the distance was just 5m (or less).
We ascend with Ronan, Ruth and Richard and Richard counted the number of lines tied to the bow and we decided on one and we went up. The current was getting stronger and we were all hanging on for our dear lives. Got up to the surface and it was the wrong boat (Red Sea Agressor 2) and the crew member signalled Blue Melody to come and pick us up.
One of Blue Melody crews came to pick us up in a zodiac and threw a rope to us, Oisin caught it mid-air and passed the line to me. I tried to throw the line to the next diver behind me but unfortunately the zodiac has drifted away by then. We were towed back to the Blue Melody and I only had 10 bar of air left.
Our guide moussa came to us and said he was worried for us and was looking for us.
The bar was opened that night to celebrate our safe return.
